news/articles/2024-08-02/character-ai-co-founders-hired-by-google-in-licens=
ing-deal=3Fcmpid=3DBBD080524_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_source=3Dnew=
sletter&utm_term=3D240805&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A:=0A=0ACharacter.AI=
=E2=80=99s co-founders are joining Google in a larger deal that will allow =
=0Athe search giant to license the artificial intelligence startup=E2=80=99=
s technology.=0A=0ACharacter.AI, a startup known for chatbots that can mimi=
c anyone or anything, =0Aannounced the news in a blog post on Friday. Found=
ers Noam Shazeer and Daniel =0ADe Freitas, along with some members of its r=
esearch team, will join Alphabet =0AInc.=E2=80=99s Google, the company said=
. The startup=E2=80=99s new interim chief executive =0Aofficer will be Dom=
inic Perella, who had been Character.AI=E2=80=99s general counsel. =E2=80=
=A6=0A=0AThe Menlo Park, California-based startup will enter into a non-exc=
lusive =0Alicensing deal with Google for its large language model technolog=
y, it said. =0AAnd Character.AI will continue to exist. =E2=80=9CMost of Ch=
aracter.AI=E2=80=99s talented team =0Awill remain and will continue to buil=
d the Character.AI product and serve our =0Agrowing base of users,=E2=80=9D=
 the startup wrote in the blog post.=0A=0ACharacter.AI is not the only buzz=
y AI startup to see its founders go to a =0Alarge tech company as the race =
for AI talent and technology accelerates. =0AMicrosoft Corp. hired two co-f=
ounders of AI startup Inflection AI along with =0Amuch of its staff in Marc=
h. And in June Amazon brought on top executives and =0Aother employees from=
 startup Adept AI Labs Inc. for its AGI autonomy team.=0A=0AFor Character.A=
I=E2=80=99s founders, the deal represents a homecoming of sorts. =0AShazeer=
 and De Freitas both previously worked at Google. During his first stint =
=0Aat the tech giant, Shazeer co-authored =E2=80=9CAttention Is All You Nee=
d,=E2=80=9D a seminal =0Apaper on generative AI. But as of July 2023, all e=
ight authors of the paper had =0Aleft Google, many launching high-profile A=
I startups of their own.=0A=0AThese deals are sort of acquisitions, in that=
 the startups=E2=80=99 investors get =0Apaid, but they are disappointing re=
lative to those investors=E2=80=99 ambitions.The =0AInformation reports =0A=
<https://www.theinformation.com/articles/google-hires-character-ai-cofounde=
rs-and-licenses-its-models=3Frc=3D1bdi5h>=0A:=0A=0ACharacter=E2=80=99s lead=
ers told staff on Friday that investors would be bought out at =0Aa valuati=
on of about $88 per share. That=E2=80=99s about 2.5 times the value of shar=
es =0Ain Character=E2=80=99s 2023 Series A, which valued the company at $1 =
billion, they =0Asaid. =E2=80=A6=0A=0AThe deal follows a string of similar =
arrangements by other well-funded =0Aartificial intelligence startups. AI d=
evelopers Adept and Inflection have both =0Aeffectively sold themselves to =
Amazon and Microsoft, respectively, in the last =0Afive months despite rais=
ing considerable capital.=0A=0ASuch deals can return investors=E2=80=99 mon=
ey, as in Inflection=E2=80=99s case, but they=E2=80=99re =0Afar from the bi=
g payouts that venture investors seek when they fund a company.=0A=0AAs the=
 Information reported about the Inflection deal =0A<https://www.theinformat=
ion.com/articles/microsoft-agreed-to-pay-inflection-650-million-while-hirin=
g-its-staff=3Frc=3D1bdi5h>=0A:=0A=0AThese deals, whose terms are often clos=
ely guarded, have given big tech =0Acompanies access to highly coveted AI t=
echnology and researchers. They have =0Aalso allowed those big companies to=
 sidestep the type of antitrust scrutiny =0Athat waylaid potential tech acq=
uisitions such as Adobe=E2=80=99s $20 billion attempted =0Apurchase of desi=
gn software company Figma. The Federal Trade Commission, =0Ahowever, has re=
cently said it is looking into some of the cloud providers=E2=80=99 =0Astar=
tup investments.=0A=0A=E2=80=9CThis is the new way the Magnificent Seven [t=
ech stocks] are going to do =0Aacquisitions, you get the [intellectual prop=
erty] and team without FTC scrutiny =0Aor approval,=E2=80=9D said Venky Gan=
esan, a managing director at Menlo Ventures, which =0Arecently led an inves=
tment in Anthropic, a rival to Inflection that has =0Areceived funding from=
 Google and Amazon.=0A=0AI suppose one way to think about it is that the cu=
rrent AI boom creates huge =0Ademand fortalent, for ideas and for computing=
 power, but has not generated a =0Aton of, like, standalone consumer-facing=
products. I enjoy ChatGPT, but =E2=80=9Cyour =0Adeveloper tools write code =
for you=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cyour spreadsheet builds models for you=E2=80=
=9D =0Aor =E2=80=9Cyour search engine just tells you the answer=E2=80=9D ar=
e all arguably better =0Aexperiences than =E2=80=9Cyou open up a website to=
 ask it how to write code.=E2=80=9D For a =0Agiant tech company, licensing =
the underlying technology and putting it into =0Ayour own widely adopted pr=
oducts might make more sense than acquiring an AI =0Astartup=E2=80=99s prod=
uct. Plus the startup is probably paying you for computing power =0Aanyway.=
=0A=0AWhat should you make of this if you are an investor in AI startups=3F=
 (What =0Ashould you make of it if you are the FTC=3F) Is the takeaway some=
thing like =E2=80=9Cwe =0Aare pumping money into companies so that they can=
 spend it on Alphabet=E2=80=99s or =0AMicrosoft=E2=80=99s or Amazon=E2=80=
=99s computing power, build some cool AI technology, and =0Athen get hired =
back at Alphabet or Microsoft or Amazon at higher salaries=E2=80=9D=3F Are =
=0Aventure investors subsidizing Google=E2=80=99s research budget, and gett=
ing Google =0Aresearchers nice raises=3F=0A=0A=0ADJT=0A=0AThere are basical=
ly two kinds of public companies in the US, which you can =0Adistinguish fr=
om each other by looking at their lists of top shareholders. Big =0Ainstitu=
tional investors, and some individuals, have to report their stock =0Aholdi=
ngs, and those reports get aggregated, by Bloomberg among others. So when =
=0AI look at Bloomberg=E2=80=99s ownership page for JPMorgan Chase & Co., f=
or instance, I =0Asee shareholders that include BlackRock and Vanguard and =
State Street, the =E2=80=9CBig =0AThree=E2=80=9D index investors, but also =
big actively managed institutions like Capital =0AGroup and Fidelity and T.=
 Rowe Price. Also, though, when I look at the top of =0Athe page, I see tha=
t about 77% of the shares are accounted for: Institutions =0Aand individual=
s who report their share ownership own 77% of JPMorgan.=0A=0AAnd then when =
I look at AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc., a big meme stock, I =0Asee that =
only about 27% of the shares are accounted for: A large majority of =0AAMC=
=E2=80=99s holders are retail investors who do not have to disclose their o=
wnership, =0Aso public ownership data is much sparser. At AMC too, the top =
holders include =0Athe Big Three index investors. But the rest of the top i=
nstitutions are mostly =0Anot long-term asset managers like Fidelity or T. =
Rowe, but fast-money hedge =0Afunds like Renaissance Technologies and DE Sh=
aw & Co., or proprietary trading =0Afirms like Jane Street Group and Susque=
hanna International Group. Most of those =0Afirms don=E2=80=99t own that st=
ock as a long-term investment: They own that stock =0Abecause they are esse=
ntially taking the other side of very active retail =0Atraders, in the stoc=
k or in options. (Quite possibly they own the stock to =0Ahedge options the=
y have sold to retail traders.). Also they don=E2=80=99t own thatmuch =0Aof=
 it; that=E2=80=99s a market-making position, not an investment.=0A=0ALast =
week, New York magazine had a very fun profile =0A<https://nymag.com/intell=
igencer/article/donald-trump-truth-social-djt-stock-corruption.html>=0A of =
Trump Media & Technology Group, Donald Trump=E2=80=99s small business that =
is also =0Aa large meme stock. (=E2=80=9C=E2=80=98It=E2=80=99s a company th=
at essentially has the revenue of not =0Aeven a medium-size McDonald=E2=80=
=99s franchise,=E2=80=99 says John Rekenthaler, a researcher =0Aat Mornings=
tar,=E2=80=9D but its market capitalization today is more than $5 billion.)=
 =0AThere is a lot about its fairly hapless founding by formerApprentice =
=0Acontestants, its struggles to go public by merging with a special purpos=
e =0Aacquisition company, etc.:=0A=0AThe upshot was that even with the SPAC=
 maneuver and its $300 million in limbo, =0Athere would be enough capital t=
o build a social network. And the executives had =0Adecided on a name. At a=
 meeting at Trump=E2=80=99s golf club in Bedminster, New Jersey, =0AMoss an=
d Litinsky pitched him on Virt, short for virtuous. Trump suggested =0ATrut=
h instead. They looked up the domain TruthSocial.com, saw that it was =0Aav=
ailable for a little more than $2,000, and bought it. When they ran the nam=
e =0Aby Melania, she burst out laughing. =E2=80=9CTruth=3F!=E2=80=9D she sa=
id, pointing at her =0Ahusband. =E2=80=9CThis guy=3F=E2=80=9D=0A=0AAnd the =
story makes the reasonable point that, if Donald Trump becomes =0Apresident=
 again and you want to bribe him, Trump Media gives you some good ways =0At=
o do so: A really ambitious bidder could try to acquire the company and cas=
h =0Aout Trump=E2=80=99s multi-billion dollar stake, but even short of that=
 you could buy =0Astock to show your support, buy advertising on Truth Soci=
al, etc. If you=E2=80=99re an =0Ainstitution, your stock ownership would be=
 public, so Trump could see it and be =0Agrateful.=0A=0AThis, though, is pr=
obably not that:=0A=0AIn March, Trump announced a surprising policy reversa=
l. As president, he=E2=80=99d =0Atried to ban TikTok, which is owned by a C=
hinese company; now, abruptly, he was =0Afor the social network=E2=80=99s c=
ontinued operation. The about-face followed a meeting =0ATrump took with Je=
ff Yass, a major Republican donor who owns a significant =0Astake in TikTok=
=E2=80=99s parent. When reporters dug up the fact that his trading firm, =
=0ASusquehanna International Group, had until recently been the single-larg=
est =0Ainstitutional shareholder in Digital World, there was outrage: Here =
was a =0Aseemingly perfect example of a billionaire using Trump=E2=80=99s c=
ompany to influence =0Ahim. Susquehanna has since insisted that its 2 perce=
nt stake was offset by =0Aequivalent short positions and that it had =E2=80=
=9Czero economic interest in Trump =0AMedia.=E2=80=9D Even if that were tru=
e, taking multibillion-dollar investment firms at =0Atheir word is hardly a=
 model for good government.=0A=0AI have no inside information here, but I w=
ill take Susquehanna at their word=3F =0ASusquehanna is fundamentally a mar=
ket maker: If it=E2=80=99s long 2% of Trump Media, =0Athat=E2=80=99s almost=
 certainly because it=E2=80=99s also short 2% of Trump Media (or has sold =
=0Aoptions, etc.). Susquehanna being a big holder of Trump Media doesn=E2=
=80=99t actually =0Amean that Susquehanna is a big investor in Trump Media.=
 It means that Trump =0AMedia is a meme stock, and it doesn=E2=80=99t reall=
